The NanoRacks '''Bishop Airlock Module''' is a [[Commercial use of space|commercially]]-funded [[airlock]] module intended to be launched to the [[International Space Station]] on [[SpaceX CRS-19]] in 2019.<ref>http://nanoracks.com/nanoracks-adds-thales-alenia-space-to-airlock/</ref> The module is being built by [[NanoRacks]] and [[Boeing]],<ref name="NanoRacks">{{cite web|url=http://nanoracks.com/nanoracks-boeing-first-commercial-airlock-module-on-iss/|title=NanoRacks, Boeing to Build First Commercial ISS Airlock Module|publisher=}}</ref> and will be used to deploy [[CubeSat]]s, small satellites, and other external payloads for [[NASA]], [[CASIS]], and other commercial and governmental customers. It will be delivered to the ISS via a [[Commercial Resupply Services]] mission.<ref name="NASA Announcement">{{cite web|url=https://www.nasa.gov/feature/progress-underway-for-first-commercial-airlock-on-space-station|title=Progress Underway for First Commercial Airlock on Space Station|first=Mark|last=Garcia|date=3 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

==Background==
Under the International Space Station's designation as a facility of the [[Center for the Advancement of Science in Space]] [[Federal government of the United States|US government]]-funded national laboratory, NanoRacks has an agreement with NASA to send payloads from academic and private sources for installation on the ISS' experiment racks or deployment from the equipment airlock in the [[JAXA|Japanese]] [[Kibo (ISS module)|Kibo]] module. Limitations on NASA's use of the JAXA facility created a bottleneck, prompting NanoRacks to develop their own airlock to increase satellite deployment capabilities.<ref name="Ars Technica">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2016/01/to-boost-commercial-activity-nasa-may-add-private-airlock-to-iss/|title=To boost commercial activity, NASA may add private airlock to ISS|publisher=}}</ref> A [[Space Act Agreement]] between NASA and NanoRacks to develop a private airlock was signed in May 2016,<ref name="NanoRacks"/> and the NanoRacks-Boeing plan to build and launch the module by 2019 was approved in February 2017.<ref name="NASA Announcement"/>

